- [🚨 Detection Gaps & Recommendations](#-detection-gaps--recommendations)

•	No alert fired on a RemoteInteractive logon from an unrecognized external IP for an account with no remote-work profile — this should be a high-fidelity detection signal.
•	No alert fired on lateral movement (RDP) from a billing workstation to a file server and IT workstation — an atypical cross-functional access pattern.
•	No DLP or alerting coverage on payroll/HR data being moved into an unrelated business share (Billing) under a disguised filename.
•	No alerting on sequential native-tool recon bursts (whoami, net, arp, nslookup) executed by a single account in a short time window.
•	SMB-level file event visibility on NH-FS-01 required additional query tuning during this hunt, suggesting file-share auditing configuration should be reviewed for completeness.

- [🧾 Final Assessment](#-final-assessment)
The following factors are confirmed by direct evidence:
•	A live human operator drove this activity interactively — not automated malware — based on native tool usage and human-paced command sequencing.
•	The account used valid, functioning credentials for j.morris; there is no indication of brute-force or credential-guessing activity (no elevated failed-login counts preceded the successful logon).
•	The RemoteInteractive logon modality is not part of j.morris's normal working pattern — remote or hybrid work is not an assumed part of this role's day-to-day, making any RemoteInteractive session for this account inherently anomalous, independent of geography.
•	The systems accessed (file server, IT workstation) are adjacent to but outside j.morris's normal job function as a billing analyst, and the operator needed to actively discover hostnames, permissions, and available shares — behavior inconsistent with routine, authorized use by the account's normal user.
•	No malware installation, exploit activity, or email/mailbox compromise indicators (phishing clicks, malicious mail rules, anomalous OAuth grants) were found on any monitored asset tied to this account.
What this does and does not establish:
The absence of on-network malware or email-compromise indicators does not rule out credential theft — it indicates the initial compromise likely occurred outside the organization's monitored environment. Common mechanisms consistent with this evidence include third-party credential exposure (e.g., password reuse from an unrelated external breach) or off-network phishing (e.g., a personal device or personal account not covered by corporate monitoring). The specific initial access vector could not be conclusively determined from available telemetry.
Separately, the identity of the operator behind the keyboard — an external threat actor using stolen credentials, versus a different internal party misusing j.morris's account — remains unresolved. The external origin IP (Los Angeles) is evidence consistent with, though not exclusive to, an external actor; internal misuse via VPN, proxy, or remote-access infrastructure cannot be fully excluded without additional corroborating evidence (e.g., known VPN/proxy associations for that IP, or HR/badge/travel records placing j.morris elsewhere at the time).
Recommended classification for reporting purposes: “Confirmed compromised-credential intrusion (T1078/T1078.002); initial access vector outside monitored environment; operator identity unresolved.” This is deliberately more precise than either “curious employee with leftover access” (not supported — the evidence shows deliberate reconnaissance, concealment, and staged data theft, not accidental access) or an unqualified “insider threat” finding (not fully supported — the anomalous logon modality and external IP are equally consistent with a genuinely external actor).

