## 🧠 Hunt Overview

Threat hunting activity identified unauthorized use of valid domain credentials belonging to j.morris, a billing analyst, to access systems and data well outside that role's normal scope. The activity began with a successful RemoteInteractive logon from an external IP address (193.36.225.245, geolocated to Los Angeles) with no preceding failed attempts, followed by a structured reconnaissance sequence, lateral movement into the file server and an IT workstation, and access to both fraudulent billing data and HR/payroll records. Material appears to have been assembled for a follow-on spearphishing or privilege-escalation attempt against a second employee, d.patel.
No malware, dropped payloads, exploit activity, or persistence mechanisms were identified on any involved host. All actions were carried out using native, signed Windows utilities (whoami, net, arp, nslookup), consistent with a live human operator working interactively rather than automated tooling.
This activity is assessed with high confidence as valid-account abuse (MITRE ATT&CK T1078 / T1078.002). The identity and origin of the operator — whether an external party using stolen credentials, or an internal party misusing j.morris's account — could not be conclusively determined from available telemetry and is discussed in Section 4.


